00:29:25.530 --> 00:29:31.900
Alright, so now let's take our
microstate energy here.

00:29:31.900 --> 00:29:35.870
And our microstate energy is the
sum of all the molecular

00:29:35.870 --> 00:29:39.470
energies Ei.

00:29:39.470 --> 00:29:56.870
So it's the sum of all
energies E sub,

00:29:56.870 --> 00:29:59.190
over all the atoms.

00:29:59.190 --> 00:30:02.580
And each one of these energies,
if it's a molecular

00:30:02.580 --> 00:30:08.460
energies, can be indexed by a
quantum number of some sort.

00:30:08.460 --> 00:30:13.760
So it would be the sum
over all energies.

00:30:13.760 --> 00:30:18.760
So quantum number for particle
one, n1 is some sort of

00:30:18.760 --> 00:30:21.660
quantum number. n2 is some sort
of quantum number. n3 is

00:30:21.660 --> 00:30:23.190
some sort of quantum number.

00:30:23.190 --> 00:30:26.460
And then you have all
the molecules.

00:30:26.460 --> 00:30:31.200
En1 plus En2 plus
En3, et cetera.

00:30:31.200 --> 00:30:34.250
So this is the energy from
molecule one, energy from

00:30:34.250 --> 00:30:36.430
molecule two, energy from
molecule three, energy from

00:30:36.430 --> 00:30:37.390
molecule four.

00:30:37.390 --> 00:30:40.230
And that little n tells you
which energy state that

00:30:40.230 --> 00:30:42.260
molecule is.

00:30:42.260 --> 00:30:47.050
And the sum of all
these energies is

00:30:47.050 --> 00:30:49.310
your microstate energy.

00:30:49.310 --> 00:30:51.890
As long as you can write this
this way, then you're allowed

00:30:51.890 --> 00:30:57.220
to write this this way.

00:30:57.220 --> 00:30:59.840
So that basically means that
they're not interacting with

00:30:59.840 --> 00:31:00.700
each other.

00:31:00.700 --> 00:31:02.630
They're independent
from each other.

00:31:02.630 --> 00:31:03.900
In this case here.

00:31:03.900 --> 00:31:09.900
So now if I write Q in terms
of the sum over all

00:31:09.900 --> 00:31:16.550
microstates Ei. e to the
minus Ei over kT.

00:31:16.550 --> 00:31:20.290
I'm going to replace this Ei
here with the sum over all

00:31:20.290 --> 00:31:22.010
these energies here.

00:31:22.010 --> 00:31:24.830
And so the sum over all
microstates, then, becomes the

00:31:24.830 --> 00:31:28.210
sum over all possible
combinations of quantum

00:31:28.210 --> 00:31:37.090
numbers. n1, n2, n3,
n4, et cetera.

00:31:37.090 --> 00:31:40.180
All the possible
ways of getting

00:31:40.180 --> 00:31:41.830
molecule one in some state.

00:31:41.830 --> 00:31:44.330
All the possible ways of getting
molecule two in some

00:31:44.330 --> 00:31:45.850
quantum number state.

00:31:45.850 --> 00:31:51.050
And then e to the minus -- and
instead of capital Ei, I'm

00:31:51.050 --> 00:31:54.080
going to write the molecular
energies.

00:31:54.080 --> 00:32:00.040
En1, plus En2, plus epsilon
n3 plus et cetera.

00:32:00.040 --> 00:32:06.200
And then divide by kT.

00:32:06.200 --> 00:32:10.270
Basically I'm going to prove
that this is a fine statement

00:32:10.270 --> 00:32:17.260
to make, as long as you can
write the energy as a sum of

00:32:17.260 --> 00:32:26.380
component energies.

00:32:26.380 --> 00:32:29.840
OK so now this term here, e to
the minus En1, only cares

00:32:29.840 --> 00:32:31.340
about this sum here.

00:32:31.340 --> 00:32:33.590
En2, that's molecule number
two, only cares

00:32:33.590 --> 00:32:35.130
about this sum here.

00:32:35.130 --> 00:32:37.320
Molecule number three only cares
about the sum over all

00:32:37.320 --> 00:32:38.790
possible quantum numbers
connected to

00:32:38.790 --> 00:32:40.000
molecule number three.

00:32:40.000 --> 00:32:47.970
So I can factor out all these
sums into a factor of sums.

00:32:47.970 --> 00:32:51.220
Is equal to the sum over quantum
number n1. e to the

00:32:51.220 --> 00:32:58.780
minus epsilon of n1,
divided by kT.

00:32:58.780 --> 00:33:10.104
Times n2 e to the minus epsilon
n2 over kT, times n3 e

00:33:10.104 --> 00:33:13.200
to the minus epsilon n3 divided
by kT, et cetera.

00:33:13.200 --> 00:33:15.750
And now each one of these is
basically the molecular

00:33:15.750 --> 00:33:16.500
partition function.

00:33:16.500 --> 00:33:21.180
These are all the possible
energies of that molecule.

00:33:21.180 --> 00:33:24.340
And the sum over all possible
energies times e to the minus

00:33:24.340 --> 00:33:26.860
E over kT is the partition
function for the molecule.

00:33:26.860 --> 00:33:31.190
So we have q for molecule one
times q for molecule two.

00:33:31.190 --> 00:33:32.900
And they're all the same.

00:33:32.900 --> 00:33:34.630
There are N of them.

00:33:34.630 --> 00:33:42.190
Plus q to the N. So just, in a
way, clarified that the reason

00:33:42.190 --> 00:33:46.170
why we're able to write this
system partition function, in

00:33:46.170 --> 00:33:50.840
terms of the molecular partition
functions, with N of

00:33:50.840 --> 00:33:53.410
them, to the Nth power, is
because we were able to

00:33:53.410 --> 00:33:55.320
separate out the energy here.

00:33:55.320 --> 00:33:58.550
In terms of the independent
molecular energies.

00:33:58.550 --> 00:34:01.280
Where this is saying the
molecules don't interact with

00:34:01.280 --> 00:34:02.570
each other.

00:34:02.570 --> 00:34:04.410
And are independent
from each other.

00:34:04.410 --> 00:34:07.700
And then the one over N
factorial comes in, so that

00:34:07.700 --> 00:34:12.930
you don't over count, for
translation, the positions.

00:34:12.930 --> 00:34:21.360
They're indistinguishable.

00:34:21.360 --> 00:34:22.070
OK.

00:34:22.070 --> 00:34:23.320
So now we can have --

00:34:23.320 --> 00:34:25.100
Actually we're not --

00:34:25.100 --> 00:34:30.560
This basic concept of the
partition function multiplying

00:34:30.560 --> 00:34:36.310
each other, if the energies add,
is not limited to going

00:34:36.310 --> 00:34:39.710
from the molecular partition
functions to the system

00:34:39.710 --> 00:34:40.440
partition function.

00:34:40.440 --> 00:34:43.250
You can also look
at the molecular

00:34:43.250 --> 00:34:45.090
partition function itself.

00:34:45.090 --> 00:34:49.120
And if the energy, the molecular
energy, can be

00:34:49.120 --> 00:34:53.770
written in terms of a sum of
energies of different degrees

00:34:53.770 --> 00:34:56.744
of freedom, for instance, the
energy of a molecule could be

00:34:56.744 --> 00:34:58.560
the energy of the vibration,
plus the energy of the

00:34:58.560 --> 00:35:01.685
translation, plus the energy
of the rotation, plus the

00:35:01.685 --> 00:35:03.596
energy of the magnetic field,
plus the energy of the

00:35:03.596 --> 00:35:04.410
electric field. et cetera.

00:35:04.410 --> 00:35:07.520
You have many energies that can
add up with each other to

00:35:07.520 --> 00:35:10.640
create the molecular energy.

00:35:10.640 --> 00:35:14.320
And what we're going to be able
to write, then, is that

00:35:14.320 --> 00:35:17.270
this molecular partition
function itself can be written

00:35:17.270 --> 00:35:22.310
in terms of a product of
partition functions for the

00:35:22.310 --> 00:35:25.680
sub parts of the molecular
energy.

00:35:25.680 --> 00:35:40.520
So let me clarify
that statement.

00:35:40.520 --> 00:35:46.350
So if I can write my molecular
energy, epsilon, is equal to a

00:35:46.350 --> 00:35:51.790
translational energy, plus a
vibrational energy, plus a

00:35:51.790 --> 00:35:55.090
rotational energy, plus every
other little energies that you

00:35:55.090 --> 00:35:58.730
can think of that are
independent of each other.

00:35:58.730 --> 00:36:03.640
Then using the same argument we
used to show that Q is the

00:36:03.640 --> 00:36:07.550
multiplication of these
molecular partition function,

00:36:07.550 --> 00:36:11.300
we can write that the molecular
partition function,

00:36:11.300 --> 00:36:18.120
little q, is just the
multiplication of the degree

00:36:18.120 --> 00:36:19.410
of freedom partition
functions --

00:36:19.410 --> 00:36:20.490
molecular partition functions.

00:36:20.490 --> 00:36:23.810
The translational partition
function times the vibrational

00:36:23.810 --> 00:36:28.200
partition function, times
the rotational partition

00:36:28.200 --> 00:36:29.670
function, et cetera.

00:36:29.670 --> 00:36:32.910
If the energies add, then the
partition functions multiply

00:36:32.910 --> 00:36:36.190
each other.

00:36:36.190 --> 00:36:37.830
And that's going to be powerful
because when we look

00:36:37.830 --> 00:36:43.220
at something like a polymer or
DNA or protein or something,

00:36:43.220 --> 00:36:44.490
in solution.

00:36:44.490 --> 00:36:46.710
And we're going to be looking at
the configurations possible

00:36:46.710 --> 00:36:52.970
for that polymer or that
biopolymer, then we'll know

00:36:52.970 --> 00:36:56.938
that the energy of that polymer
in solution is going

00:36:56.938 --> 00:37:00.010
to be -- we'll be able to
approximate it as the energy

00:37:00.010 --> 00:37:03.653
of the configuration
for that polymer.

00:37:03.653 --> 00:37:06.030
The different ways that
you can fold the

00:37:06.030 --> 00:37:08.210
protein, for instance.

00:37:08.210 --> 00:37:10.050
Plus everything else.

00:37:10.050 --> 00:37:14.880
The energy of everything else.

00:37:14.880 --> 00:37:15.300
OK.

00:37:15.300 --> 00:37:18.530
So if the configurational energy
can be separated from

00:37:18.530 --> 00:37:21.070
the sum of all vibration
energies of all the bonds in

00:37:21.070 --> 00:37:22.380
that polymer.

00:37:22.380 --> 00:37:26.290
The way that polymer
interacts with --

00:37:26.290 --> 00:37:30.840
The way that the solution itself
interacts with itself.

00:37:30.840 --> 00:37:34.780
Then if we can do this and we
can do this approximation most

00:37:34.780 --> 00:37:38.000
of the time, then we'll be able
to take the partition

00:37:38.000 --> 00:37:40.590
function for the polymer,
and write it as the

00:37:40.590 --> 00:37:43.610
configurational partition
function times the partition

00:37:43.610 --> 00:37:45.750
function for everything else.

00:37:45.750 --> 00:37:55.750
And we'll find that this part
here will tend to factor out.

00:37:55.750 --> 00:37:58.660
We won't have to
worry about it.

00:37:58.660 --> 00:38:01.380
And that this will carry all the
important information that

00:38:01.380 --> 00:38:05.220
we'll need to know to see about
changes in the system.

00:38:05.220 --> 00:38:07.055
Changes in Gibbs free
energy, changes in

00:38:07.055 --> 00:38:08.110
the chemical potential.

00:38:08.110 --> 00:38:12.620
Everything will be related to
this partition function.

00:38:12.620 --> 00:38:14.060
This subsystem.

00:38:14.060 --> 00:38:19.575
And because of the fact that you
can factor them out, then

00:38:19.575 --> 00:38:21.770
this thing will end
up dropping out.

00:38:21.770 --> 00:38:30.310
And this will become the
important factor.

00:38:30.310 --> 00:38:30.970
OK.

00:38:30.970 --> 00:38:55.860
Let's do a quick example.

00:38:55.860 --> 00:38:56.100
OK.

00:38:56.100 --> 00:39:00.670
So this is the example
of having a

00:39:00.670 --> 00:39:02.260
very very, short polymer.

00:39:02.260 --> 00:39:06.330
Containing three monomers.

00:39:06.330 --> 00:39:13.850
Which can be in two
configurations.

00:39:13.850 --> 00:39:17.060
And the energies are the same
for these two configurations.

00:39:17.060 --> 00:39:21.200
So the configurational partition
function, which you

00:39:21.200 --> 00:39:26.690
would generally write as the sum
of e to the minus Ei for

00:39:26.690 --> 00:39:29.680
that configuration, divided
by kT, plus e to the --

00:39:29.680 --> 00:39:34.500
So we would usually write it as
e to the minus epsilon one

00:39:34.500 --> 00:39:38.373
over kT, plus e to the
minus epsilon two

00:39:38.373 --> 00:39:41.100
over kT, plus et cetera.

00:39:41.100 --> 00:39:43.890
They're all the same energy.

00:39:43.890 --> 00:39:45.780
And there are two
configurations.

00:39:45.780 --> 00:39:47.950
The degeneracy is two.

00:39:47.950 --> 00:39:50.640
So you can write this as
the degeneracy of the

00:39:50.640 --> 00:39:55.820
configuration, times the energy
of the configuration.

00:39:55.820 --> 00:40:00.070
And you can set your energy
reference to be zero.

00:40:00.070 --> 00:40:01.870
You can choose whatever
you want it to be.

00:40:01.870 --> 00:40:03.170
And zero is a good number.

00:40:03.170 --> 00:40:05.380
So that e to the zero
is equal to one.

00:40:05.380 --> 00:40:07.980
So that configuration partition
function is just the

00:40:07.980 --> 00:40:23.060
degeneracy, which is equal to
two, in this case here.

00:40:23.060 --> 00:40:32.740
So now let's calculate the
molecular and canonical

00:40:32.740 --> 00:40:38.760
partition functions for
an ideal gas of

00:40:38.760 --> 00:40:41.540
these molecules here.

00:40:41.540 --> 00:40:44.600
And it's usually interesting
to use a

00:40:44.600 --> 00:40:47.110
lattice model as a guide.

00:40:47.110 --> 00:40:50.960
And so in this lattice model
here, you would divide space

00:40:50.960 --> 00:40:55.040
up into little cells.

00:40:55.040 --> 00:40:57.940
Pieces in two dimensions, but
in reality it would be three

00:40:57.940 --> 00:40:58.800
dimensions.

00:40:58.800 --> 00:41:03.510
And then you place your
molecules in lattice sites.

00:41:03.510 --> 00:41:06.470
Something like this.

00:41:06.470 --> 00:41:09.280
And then you end up counting
the number of ways of

00:41:09.280 --> 00:41:12.810
arranging the molecules
on the lattice.

00:41:12.810 --> 00:41:16.540
And let's say that we have
N molecules that

00:41:16.540 --> 00:41:18.930
are in the gas phase.

00:41:18.930 --> 00:41:26.580
And the molecular volume, i.e.
the size of the lattice site

00:41:26.580 --> 00:41:31.310
is v. That's the molecular
volume.

00:41:31.310 --> 00:41:36.640
And N times v is the
total volume.

00:41:36.640 --> 00:41:41.970
That's the total volume occupied
by the particles.

00:41:41.970 --> 00:41:43.970
The total volume is the number
of lattice sites.

00:41:43.970 --> 00:41:56.500
V is the total volume.

00:41:56.500 --> 00:42:01.620
And we're going to assume that
all particles, all molecules

00:42:01.620 --> 00:42:03.890
have the same translation
energy.

00:42:03.890 --> 00:42:05.850
It's an adequate
approximation.

00:42:05.850 --> 00:42:08.790
We're going to set that
equal to zero.

00:42:08.790 --> 00:42:12.770
So all molecules at any position
here has the same E

00:42:12.770 --> 00:42:15.590
translation.

00:42:15.590 --> 00:42:20.590
And we're going to set
that equal to zero.

00:42:20.590 --> 00:42:23.400
So the translational
partition function.

00:42:23.400 --> 00:42:33.750
The molecular transitional
partition function is --

00:42:33.750 --> 00:42:35.420
Well there's only one energy.

00:42:35.420 --> 00:42:36.930
It's zero.

00:42:36.930 --> 00:42:40.020
So we only care about the
degeneracy of that molecule.

00:42:40.020 --> 00:42:44.800
That molecule could be in here,
or it could be here, it

00:42:44.800 --> 00:42:46.920
could be here, it could
be here, it could

00:42:46.920 --> 00:42:48.370
be anywhere, right?

00:42:48.370 --> 00:42:52.910
The number of ways of putting
that molecule on the lattice

00:42:52.910 --> 00:42:55.310
is the number of lattice
sites available.

00:42:55.310 --> 00:42:58.200
Which is basically the
molecular volume.

00:42:58.200 --> 00:42:59.750
Which is the total
volume divided by

00:42:59.750 --> 00:43:02.720
the molecular volume.

00:43:02.720 --> 00:43:15.580
The total volume is -- right.

00:43:15.580 --> 00:43:23.870
So the total volume is the
number of lattice sites times

00:43:23.870 --> 00:43:26.980
the volume of each
lattice site.

00:43:26.980 --> 00:43:30.420
So the total volume divided by
the small volume is the total

00:43:30.420 --> 00:43:32.030
number of lattice sites.

00:43:32.030 --> 00:43:34.630
And the number of choices of
putting that one molecule is

00:43:34.630 --> 00:43:39.470
anywhere on the lattice.

00:43:39.470 --> 00:43:44.330
That's your degeneracy.

00:43:44.330 --> 00:43:50.810
So now if I look at the total
molecular partition function,

00:43:50.810 --> 00:43:52.710
it's going to be the
multiplication of the

00:43:52.710 --> 00:43:55.640
configurational partition
function and the translational

00:43:55.640 --> 00:43:58.260
partition function.

00:43:58.260 --> 00:44:18.100
At each site, the molecule could
have two configurations.

00:44:18.100 --> 00:44:22.280
So q, for the molecule, that's
q translational.

00:44:22.280 --> 00:44:23.710
I'm going to ignore
all vibrations,

00:44:23.710 --> 00:44:24.430
rotation, et cetera.

00:44:24.430 --> 00:44:26.470
I'm going to assume that there
are two degrees of freedom.

00:44:26.470 --> 00:44:29.430
Translational one, which is
basically the positional one.

00:44:29.430 --> 00:44:31.340
And then the configurational
one, which is

00:44:31.340 --> 00:44:36.170
internal to the molecule.

00:44:36.170 --> 00:44:39.880
So this one is V over v.
That's the degeneracy.

00:44:39.880 --> 00:44:42.400
Capital V over little v. The
degeneracy of placing the

00:44:42.400 --> 00:44:45.580
molecule on the lattice.

00:44:45.580 --> 00:44:49.970
And the configuration is
the degeneracy of how

00:44:49.970 --> 00:44:52.440
the molecule folds.

00:44:52.440 --> 00:44:52.750
Yes.

00:44:52.750 --> 00:45:01.730
STUDENT: [UNINTELLIGIBLE]

00:45:01.730 --> 00:45:05.980
PROFESSOR: The notes
