00:45:05.980 --> 00:45:10.390
So usually capital V is large
and little v is small.

00:45:10.390 --> 00:45:12.920
So in the notes, if we
have it in reverse,

00:45:12.920 --> 00:45:18.620
we should fix that.

00:45:18.620 --> 00:45:21.410
This is lecture 25, right?

00:45:21.410 --> 00:45:22.840
So we have q.

00:45:22.840 --> 00:45:23.930
No the notes seem to be right.

00:45:23.930 --> 00:45:31.720
Total volume is capital V,
molecular volume is little v.

00:45:31.720 --> 00:45:33.170
Where is it that wrong
in the notes?

00:45:33.170 --> 00:45:46.030
STUDENT: [UNINTELLIGIBLE]

00:45:46.030 --> 00:45:46.870
PROFESSOR: Oh look at that.

00:45:46.870 --> 00:45:51.130
My notes are different
than yours.

00:45:51.130 --> 00:45:53.910
My notes are right.

00:45:53.910 --> 00:45:57.060
OK well it's obviously
right on the web.

00:45:57.060 --> 00:45:58.720
Because this is the
latest version.

00:45:58.720 --> 00:46:03.440
Alright so flip those big
V's and little v's then.

00:46:03.440 --> 00:46:03.770
Huh.

00:46:03.770 --> 00:46:08.530
I thought they were from
the same pile.

00:46:08.530 --> 00:46:08.860
OK.

00:46:08.860 --> 00:46:15.000
So this is your molecular
partition function.

00:46:15.000 --> 00:46:20.420
And then when you look at the
system, the system partition

00:46:20.420 --> 00:46:24.510
function can also be separated
into a translation and the

00:46:24.510 --> 00:46:27.650
configuration for the system.

00:46:27.650 --> 00:46:31.020
We know what you need to do
is take all the molecular

00:46:31.020 --> 00:46:36.360
partition functions, the
transitional ones, and -- to

00:46:36.360 --> 00:46:37.010
the N factor.

00:46:37.010 --> 00:46:39.930
The number of particles.

00:46:39.930 --> 00:46:42.230
But now you have degeneracy.

00:46:42.230 --> 00:46:45.070
You've over counted.

00:46:45.070 --> 00:46:50.000
So you need to divide
this N factorial.

00:46:50.000 --> 00:46:53.130
You also have the system
partition function for the

00:46:53.130 --> 00:46:56.190
configurations.

00:46:56.190 --> 00:47:02.250
And that's q configuration to
the N. Except here we don't

00:47:02.250 --> 00:47:04.280
need to divide by one over N
factorial, because we're not

00:47:04.280 --> 00:47:07.390
over counting here.

00:47:07.390 --> 00:47:13.840
The over counting only happens
when you're placing identical

00:47:13.840 --> 00:47:18.310
particles in a lattice, and
you can swap them without

00:47:18.310 --> 00:47:19.950
making a difference.

00:47:19.950 --> 00:47:21.950
Here we talking about
configurations.

00:47:21.950 --> 00:47:23.420
When we're talking about
configurations, we're not

00:47:23.420 --> 00:47:26.660
talking about placing the
identical particles in

00:47:26.660 --> 00:47:27.440
different spots.

00:47:27.440 --> 00:47:31.390
We're just looking at these
two configurations here.

00:47:31.390 --> 00:47:33.590
And then the next particle
is two configurations.

00:47:33.590 --> 00:47:37.550
The next particle is
two configurations.

00:47:37.550 --> 00:47:38.680
So this is really important.

00:47:38.680 --> 00:47:41.200
That this N over factorial
only comes into play when

00:47:41.200 --> 00:47:41.890
you're talking about the

00:47:41.890 --> 00:47:43.790
translational degree of freedom.

00:47:43.790 --> 00:47:46.380
Not the other degrees
of freedom.

00:47:46.380 --> 00:47:48.880
And now the total system
partition function is the

00:47:48.880 --> 00:47:51.080
multiplication of these two.

00:47:51.080 --> 00:47:57.290
It ends up being capital V over
v, to the N power, over N

00:47:57.290 --> 00:47:59.820
factorial, times

00:47:59.820 --> 00:48:07.200
two to the N. OK.

00:48:07.200 --> 00:48:10.970
In general you could extend
this analysis to include

00:48:10.970 --> 00:48:15.420
vibrations, rotations, energy
in a magnetical field,

00:48:15.420 --> 00:48:18.510
electric field, et cetera.

00:48:18.510 --> 00:48:24.400
Any questions?

00:48:24.400 --> 00:48:26.520
Alright the next thing that
you're going to do then is to

00:48:26.520 --> 00:48:31.480
use this concept, as a sort of
example, as a way to begin to

00:48:31.480 --> 00:48:34.010
calculate things that you've
already calculated before.

00:48:34.010 --> 00:48:38.570
For instance, if you look at an
expansion of an ideal gas,

00:48:38.570 --> 00:48:41.740
can we now calculate
the entropy change.

00:48:41.740 --> 00:48:45.120
Not based on thermodynamics,
but based on

00:48:45.120 --> 00:48:46.330
the statistical mechanics.

00:48:46.330 --> 00:48:49.410
On the microscopic description
that we've just gone through.

00:48:49.410 --> 00:48:53.110
And it turns out that
that's what happens.

00:48:53.110 --> 00:48:54.030
That you can do that.

00:48:54.030 --> 00:48:55.090
You get the same answer.

00:48:55.090 --> 00:48:57.430
Thank god you get
the same answer.

00:48:57.430 --> 00:49:00.680
Otherwise we'd be
in big trouble.

00:49:00.680 --> 00:49:02.446
So I'm just going to set up the
problem, because I won't

00:49:02.446 --> 00:49:03.570
have time to do it.

00:49:03.570 --> 00:49:06.010
And then you can do it next
time, when Keith comes back.

00:49:06.010 --> 00:49:11.990
So the problem is going to be
the usual problem of having a

00:49:11.990 --> 00:49:20.870
volume V1 of a gas on one side,
and a vaccuum expanding

00:49:20.870 --> 00:49:23.420
to volume V2, gas.

00:49:23.420 --> 00:49:29.700
And asking what is the
entropy change.

00:49:29.700 --> 00:49:37.000
And you know that from thermo,
that delta S in this case here

00:49:37.000 --> 00:49:43.190
is nR log V2 over V1, when the
temperature is constant.

00:49:43.190 --> 00:49:44.050
That's going to be our answer.

00:49:44.050 --> 00:49:45.580
It has to be our answer.

00:49:45.580 --> 00:49:47.340
But this time, instead of
knowing the answer, we're

00:49:47.340 --> 00:49:51.040
going to calculate it
from microscopics.

00:49:51.040 --> 00:49:54.550
So what you do is you start out
with your initial state.

00:49:54.550 --> 00:50:01.080
You ask what is -- you write
down the molecular volume V.

00:50:01.080 --> 00:50:02.330
The total volume here is V1.

00:50:10.960 --> 00:50:14.420
You assume that all molecules
have the same

00:50:14.420 --> 00:50:15.830
translational energy.

00:50:15.830 --> 00:50:17.380
You set that equal to zero.

00:50:17.380 --> 00:50:20.700
The system translational energy
is equal to zero.

00:50:20.700 --> 00:50:26.910
And so the entropy for this gas
here is just the number of

00:50:26.910 --> 00:50:30.540
ways of placing the molecule
in the lattice.

00:50:30.540 --> 00:50:34.730
This model that we have of space
being separated into

00:50:34.730 --> 00:50:35.880
little cells.

00:50:35.880 --> 00:50:43.380
And so S is k log omega, where
omega is the number of ways of

00:50:43.380 --> 00:50:45.480
placing the molecules
in the lattice.

00:50:45.480 --> 00:50:50.230
Which is basically k log V,
over v. Where this is the

00:50:50.230 --> 00:51:03.170
number of lattice sites.

00:51:03.170 --> 00:51:05.940
OK.

00:51:05.940 --> 00:51:07.370
And what you're going to
do next time, then,

00:51:07.370 --> 00:51:10.250
is start from here.

00:51:10.250 --> 00:51:11.640
Calculate what it is before.

00:51:11.640 --> 00:51:15.020
Calculate what it is after, and
turn the crank, and get to

00:51:15.020 --> 00:51:16.770
the right answer.

00:51:16.770 --> 00:51:19.070
Then you're going to do the
same thing for liquids.

00:51:19.070 --> 00:51:25.590
And that'll be it for this
simple statistical mechanics.

